<h1>@HI{{aru}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<p>
<ol>
<li>@N1{{location}} @HI{{ni}} @HI{{ha}} @N2{{}} @HI{{ga}} <strong>@HI{{aru}}</strong>
<li>@N1{{}} @HI{{ha}} @N2{{location}} @HI{{ni}} <strong>@HI{{aru}}</strong>
<li><strong>@HI{{aru}}</strong> <em>predicate</em>
</p>

<h2> Definition </h2>

In the first sentence pattern, a location is presented as the topic and <strong>@HI{{aru}}</strong>
focuses on what exists. @HI{{ni}} may be dropped.
<p></p>

In the second sentence pattern, a thing is presented as the topic and <strong>@HI{{aru}}</strong>
focuses on where that thing is.
<p></p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<strong>@HI{{aru}}</strong>

<strong>@HI{{aru}}</strong> is only used to express the existence or possession of inanimate things.
For animate things, @HI{{iru}} is used.
<p></p>

The negative form of <strong>@HI{{aru}}</strong> is @HI{{nai}}.
<p></p>

When <strong>@HI{{aru}}</strong> is used to indicate having an animate object,
that object must have a close connection with the possessor.
<p></p>

When <strong>@HI{{aru}}</strong> is used to for an event such as a party, @HI{{de}}
rather than @HI{{ni}} must be used.
<p></p>

